    <language>en_US</language>
    <keyword>dot</keyword>
    <short_description>Dot product.</short_description>
    <syntax>
        <syntax_item>R = dot(A, B)</syntax_item>
        <syntax_item>R = dot(A, B, dim)</syntax_item>
    </syntax>
    <param_input>
        <param_input_item>
            <param_name>A, B</param_name>
            <param_description>numeric arrays.</param_description>
        </param_input_item>
        <param_input_item>
            <param_name>dim</param_name>
            <param_description
      >positive integer scalar: Dimension to operate along.</param_description>
        </param_input_item>
    </param_input>
    <param_output>
        <param_output_item>
            <param_name>R</param_name>
            <param_description>Scalar Dot Product.</param_description>
        </param_output_item>
    </param_output>
    <description>
        <p>
            <b>R = dot(A, B)</b> returns the scalar dot product of <b
      >A</b> and <b>B</b>.
        </p>
        <p>For real vectors</p>
        <latex>\mathbf{a}</latex>
        <p>and</p>
        <latex>\mathbf{b}</latex>
        <p>of length</p>
        <latex>n</latex>
        <p>:</p>
        <latex
    >\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} a_i b_i = a_1 b_1 + a_2 b_2 + \cdots + a_n b_n</latex>
        <p>For complex vectors, the dot product is:</p>
        <latex
    >\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \overline{a_i} b_i</latex>
        <p>where</p>
        <latex>\overline{a_i}</latex>
        <p>denotes the complex conjugate of</p>
        <latex>a_i</latex>
    </description>
        <used_function />
        <bibliography>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dot_product</bibliography>
        <examples>
            <example_item>
                <example_item_type>nelson</example_item_type>
